Quarto

Quarto enables you to weave together content and executable code into a finished document. To learn more about Quarto see https://quarto.org.

Running Code

When you click the Render button a document will be generated that includes both content and the output of embedded code. You can embed code like this:

1 + 1

You can add options to executable code like this

The echo: false option disables the printing of code (only output is displayed).

Question 1

Prior to the 2020 US Presidential Election, the ANES asked respondents what the highest level of school they completed or the highest degree they received.

Part A

Points: 2

Note

2/2

What was the most common highest level of education obtained by respondents? What was the least common? Use the education variable from the nes data set to answer these questions.

The most common highest level of education obtained by respondents was âsome post-high school, no bachelorâs degreeâ. The least common level of education obtained by respondents was âless than high school credentialâ.

ggplot(nes, aes(y = education)) + 
    geom_bar() +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
          plot.title.position = "plot") + 
    labs(
        title = "What is the highest level of school you have completed or the highest degree you have received?", 
        x = "Count of respondents",
        y = NULL,
        caption = "Source: ANES 2020 Survey"
    ) + 
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma())

Part B

Points: 2

Note

1/2

Describe the distribution of the total number of respondents that obtained each highest level of education. Include a plot of those counts.

Note

You needed to describe the distribution as a whole. These data are approximately Normally distributed.

The most common response was âsome post-high school, no bachelorâs degreeâ. Specifically, 2,790 respondents or 33.69% of respondents answered that they completed âsome post-high school [education], [but] no bachelorâs degreeâ. The second most common response was âbachelorâs degreeâ. 2,055 respondents or 24.81% of respondents answered that they completed a bachelorâs degree. The third most common response was completion of a âgraduate degreeâ. 1,592 respondents or 19.22% of respondents answered that they received a âgraduate degreeâ.

The fourth most common response was âhigh school credentialâ. 1,336 respondents or 16.13% of respondents answered that they received a â High school credentialâ. The least common response was âLess than a high school credentialâ. Specifically, 376 respondents or 4.54% of respondents answered that they received âLess than a high school credentialâ.

Question 3

Examine the following vector of (fake) student IQ test scores:

iq <- c(
  145, 139, 126, 122, 125, 130, 96, 110, 118, 118, 101, 142, 134, 124, 112, 109, 
  134, 113, 81, 113, 123, 94, 100, 136, 109, 131, 117, 110, 127, 124, 106, 124, 
  115, 133, 116, 102, 127, 117, 109, 137, 117, 90, 103, 114, 139, 101, 122, 105, 
  97, 89, 102, 108, 110, 128, 114, 112, 114, 102, 82, 101
)

Part A

Points: 3

Note

3/3

Find the five-number summary, mean, and standard deviation for these data. Do you think any of these students might be outliers in this distribution? If so, what IQ test score did they get and how do you know?

fivenum(iq)
[1]  81.0 104.0 114.0 125.5 145.0
mean(iq)
[1] 114.9833
sd(iq)
[1] 14.80093

The five number summary of the above IQ data set is 81.0, 104.0, 114.0, 125.5, and 145.0. This means that the minimum value is 81, the first quartile is at 104, the median is 114, the third quartile is 125.5, and the maximum value is 145. The mean is 114.9833, and the standard deviation is 14.80093. I do not think there are outliers. I know this because I used the outlier equation to calculate 1.5 times the interquartile range (125.5-104). I then added this amount to the third quartile and subtracted this amount from the first quartile, determining outliers would be lower than 71.75 and higher than 157.75. As there are no IQ scores less than 71.75 and greater than 157.75, there are no outliers.

Question 5

The ANES also asked respondents prior to the election to rate Joe Biden and Donald Trump on a scale from 0 to 100.

Part A

Points: 3

Note

3/3

Plot all respondentsâ answers to these two questions on a single density plot. There are several peaks in these distributions. What do these peaks have in common? What might they suggest about how people answer questions that ask them to provide a single number along a large range?

The first peak for both plots is at 0, suggesting that some respondents felt quite negatively about both candidates. Additionally, both plots feature peaks around 85. In addition to positive sentiments, this suggests that, even when asked to provide a single number along a large range, respondents tend to respond with very low numbers or higher numbers (like numbers clustered around 60-85 for example). Respondents do not tend to give low or âlow-middleâ number ratings (between 20-40).

ggplot(nes, aes(x = therm_biden)) + 
    geom_density() +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
          plot.title.position = "plot") + 
    labs(
        title = "On a scale from 0 to 100, how would you rate Joe Biden?", 
        x = "Feeling Thermometer",
        y = "Density",
        caption = "Source: ANES 2020 Survey"
    ) + 
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma())

ggplot(nes, aes(x = therm_trump)) + 
    geom_density() +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
          plot.title.position = "plot") + 
    labs(
        title = "On a scale from 0 to 100, how would you rate Donald Trump?", 
        x = "Feeling Thermometer",
        y = "Density",
        caption = "Source: ANES 2020 Survey"
    ) + 
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma())

Note

You can get them both on the same plot by doing this:

ggplot(nes) + 
    geom_density(aes(x = therm_trump), fill = "red", alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_density(aes(x = therm_biden), fill = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
          plot.title.position = "plot") + 
    labs(
        title = "On a scale from 0 to 100, how would you rate Donald Trump?", 
        x = "Feeling Thermometer",
        y = "Density",
        caption = "Source: ANES 2020 Survey"
    ) + 
    scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::label_comma())

Part B

Points: 3

Note

3/3

President Biden won this election. Would you predict this outcome from the way this representative sample responded to these questions? Provide a brief description of the reasoning behind your answer.

Based on how the sample responded to questions, I think it would be hard to certainly predict Biden would have won the election, but I do think the data slightly favors him. Out of all ratings of Joe Biden, the most frequent rating was 0. Specifically, around 20% of respondents rated Joe Biden a 0. The next two most frequently selected ratings were 85 (14.19%) and 70 (11.69%). Though these are high ratings, they were ultimately selected at a lower rate than 0. Additionally, Trumpâs ratings make the results a little less certain. For example, a large portion of survey respondents rated Trump a 0. Specifically, 3,189 respondents or 39.62% of respondents rated Trump a 0, outpacing the number of 0 ratings Biden received. This would seem to clearly suggest that Biden would likely win; however, the second most frequent rating Trump received was 100. Specifically, 1,212 respondents or 15.05% of respondents rated him a 100, followed by 10.73% of respondents rating Trump an 85. This suggests that Trump elicits strong feelings from supporters and critics alike. Thus, it would be hard to certainly predict which of the two camps would be most likely to vote. Ultimately, given the high percentage of 0 ratings for Trump, I would have predicted that Biden was likely to win.
